<l>toḻiṟpeya rellān toḻiṟpeya riyala</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>If <foreign xml:lang="ta">num</foreign> is uttered in non-case-relationship,</l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">u</foreign> [of <foreign xml:lang="ta">num</foreign>] is replaced by <foreign xml:lang="ta">ī</foreign> which joins the consonant,</l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">i</foreign> stands in the middle, and the final [<foreign xml:lang="ta">-m</foreign>] is replaced</l>
<l>by [<foreign xml:lang="ta">-r</foreign>] without a vowel ;<note place="foot">Lit. ' <foreign xml:lang="ta">r</foreign> with the dot <foreign xml:lang="ta">(puḻḻi) '.</foreign></note> then the following word</l>
<l>[joins] without change.<note place="foot">This aphorism which is a splendid example of an ordered rule, explains
          the form <foreign xml:lang="ta">nīyir</foreign> (i.e. <foreign xml:lang="ta">nī-y--i-r)</foreign>
          as derived from <foreign xml:lang="ta">num</foreign> (i.e. <foreign xml:lang="ta">n-u-m).</foreign>
          There are many implications, cf. Comment.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
